        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276945\">Oscar Cunningham</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Is.20taking.20the.20ultrapower.20a.20monad.3F/near/303108808\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Suppose we fix a nonprincipal ultrafilter on some set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span>. Then we can denote the ultrapower of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> with respect to this ultrafilter as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow></mrow><mo>∗</mo></msup><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{}^*A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>. Then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow></mrow><mo>∗</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{}^*</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is a functor and we have a canonical inclusion <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>↦</mo><msup><mrow></mrow><mo>∗</mo></msup><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A\\mapsto{}^*A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>. Is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow></mrow><mo>∗</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{}^*</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> a monad? In particular do we also have a canonical map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow></mrow><mrow><mo>∗</mo><mo>∗</mo></mrow></msup><mi>A</mi><mo>↦</mo><msup><mrow></mrow><mo>∗</mo></msup><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{}^{**}A\\mapsto{}^*A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6997em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">∗∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>? For example, can we turn a hyperhyperreal into a hyperreal?</p>\n<p>My first thought was that we can think of elements of  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow></mrow><mrow><mo>∗</mo><mo>∗</mo></mrow></msup><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{}^{**}A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">∗∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> as equivalence classes of maps <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>N</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N\\times N\\to A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>, and composing this with the identity would give us a map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N\\to A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> and hence an element of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow></mrow><mo>∗</mo></msup><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{}^*A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>. But this operation isn't well defined because it maps different elements of the same equivalence class to different places.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I'm going to say something very wrong: basically an ultrapower is just a product of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span> copies of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> quotiented by the relation generated by your ultrafilter. So you could see this as 'lists of length <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span> quotiented in some way. If <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span> is finite, a list of length <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span> of  lists of length <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span> has length <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>N</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N^2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>. So you can 'flatten the list' basically. I think the problem arises where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span> is infinite, because mapping indexes around becomes very messy</p>",
        "id": 303445680,
        "sender_full_name": "Fabrizio Genovese",
        "timestamp": 1665497230
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I was thinking about doing the mapping itself in the hyperreal world but I don't think that will help you either, most likely  the unquotiented sequences will be non-transferable for some reason and you'll end up with the same problem</p>",
        "id": 303445966,
        "sender_full_name": "Fabrizio Genovese",
        "timestamp": 1665497301
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276438\">Fabrizio Genovese</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Is.20taking.20the.20ultrapower.20a.20monad.3F/near/303445680\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276945\">Oscar Cunningham</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Is.20taking.20the.20ultrapower.20a.20monad.3F/near/303108808\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Suppose we fix a nonprincipal ultrafilter on some set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span>. Then we can denote the ultrapower of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> with respect to this ultrafilter as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow></mrow><mo>∗</mo></msup><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{}^*A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>. Then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow></mrow><mo>∗</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{}^*</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is a functor and we have a canonical inclusion <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>↦</mo><msup><mrow></mrow><mo>∗</mo></msup><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A\\mapsto{}^*A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>. Is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow></mrow><mo>∗</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{}^*</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> a monad? In particular do we also have a canonical map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow></mrow><mrow><mo>∗</mo><mo>∗</mo></mrow></msup><mi>A</mi><mo>↦</mo><msup><mrow></mrow><mo>∗</mo></msup><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{}^{**}A\\mapsto{}^*A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6997em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">∗∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>? For example, can we turn a hyperhyperreal into a hyperreal?</p>\n<p>My first thought was that we can think of elements of  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow></mrow><mrow><mo>∗</mo><mo>∗</mo></mrow></msup><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{}^{**}A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">∗∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> as equivalence classes of maps <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>N</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N\\times N\\to A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>, and composing this with the identity would give us a map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N\\to A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> and hence an element of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow></mrow><mo>∗</mo></msup><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{}^*A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>. But this operation isn't well defined because it maps different elements of the same equivalence class to different places.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I'm going to say something very wrong: basically an ultrapower is just a product of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span> copies of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> quotiented by the relation generated by your ultrafilter. So you could see this as 'lists of length <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span> quotiented in some way. If <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span> is finite, a list of length <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span> of  lists of length <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span> has length <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>N</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N^2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>. So you can 'flatten the list' basically. I think the problem arises where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span> is infinite, because mapping indexes around becomes very messy</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>BTW  as you said the problem here is the equivalence relation, if you don't have that you could flatten the infinite lists Hilbert's hotel style, but that will most likely mess your equivalence relation completely</p>",
        "id": 303446121,
        "sender_full_name": "Fabrizio Genovese",
        "timestamp": 1665497356
    }
]